Q2).what is difference between singleton and prototype scope ?
Singleton-
 Only one instance of the bean is created per Spring container.
 Spring creates the bean at container startup and reuses it every time it is needed.
 
prototype-
A new instance of the bean is created every time it is requested from the container.
Spring does not manage the complete lifecycle.

Q3).what is difference between @Repository and @Service Annotation?
@Repository
 Purpose:
Used to indicate that the class is a Data Access Object (DAO) and interacts directly with the database.
 Key Points:
	Applied to classes that handle CRUD operations using JPA, JDBC, Hibernate, etc.
Spring translates persistence exceptions into Spring’s DataAccessException (exception translation feature).
Used mostly in the repository (data) layer

@Service
 Purpose:
Used to mark a class as a service provider — it holds business logic and calls one or more repositories to fulfill operations.
 Key Points:
Indicates a class belongs to the service (business logic) layer.
Improves readability and separation of concerns.
No automatic exception translation (unlike @Repository).

